<subSubSection pageId="187" pageNumber="187" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="187" pageNumber="187">
15. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:132448" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Oecodoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Oecodoma pallida Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="187" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida">Oecodoma pallida</taxonomicName>
. B.M.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="187" pageNumber="187" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="187" pageNumber="187">
Worker major, length 2 lines. Worker minor, 1 1/2 line. - This species very closely resembles 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:192106" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Oecodoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Oecodoma hystrix (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="187" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hystrix">hystrix</taxonomicName>
; its largest worker, however, is smaller than the smallest of that species, and its small worker the most diminutive of the genus. Mr. Bates says, &quot; Very similar to the former (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:192106" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Oecodoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Oecodoma hystrix (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="187" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hystrix">hystrix</taxonomicName>
) in the number of the tho- racic spines, &amp;c, but I think a distinct species. I found a pro- cession of them in a sandy tract of ground; all the individuals were of a uniform pale colour.&quot;
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="187" pageNumber="187" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="187" pageNumber="187">Hab. Brazil (Santarem).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="187" pageNumber="187" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="187" pageNumber="187">
This is probably the worker of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:132505" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Oecodoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Oecodoma rugosa Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="187" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosa">Oe. rugosa</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
